That's when I decided to build something different - a platform that would scrape congressional data in real-time and present it in a way that actually made sense to normal people. No more hunting through PDFs or trying to decode parliamentary procedure. Just clear, accessible information about what's happening in Congress and why it matters.

Users can browse thousands of current and former congressional members, track votes in real-time, create posts about legislative activity, and participate in discussions through comments. The platform combines official Congress.gov API data with user-generated content to create an informed community around what's actually happening in Congress. Because democracy shouldn't require a political science degree to understand.

Built with React 19 and Redux Toolkit, KTR features user authentication, role-based access control, image uploads via Cloudinary, and a responsive interface for tracking and discussing what's happening in Congress. Deployed on Heroku with MongoDB Atlas for reliable, scalable infrastructure. The biggest technical challenge? Government websites aren't exactly developer-friendly, so I built a Python scraper using lxml to handle the messy HTML from House and Senate websites."
